    },
    {
      "title": "Parallel Circuit Relationships",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "Which electrical property is common across every branch in a parallel circuit?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Voltage",
            "Vt = V1 = V2",
            "Full supply voltage is received by every load",
            "Electrical pressure is the same across all branches"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What happens to the total resistance (Rt) of a circuit as you add more parallel branches?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Total resistance decreases",
            "Opposition to flow is reduced",
            "Rt becomes less than the smallest branch resistance",
            "More paths are provided for current to flow"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "How do you calculate the total current (It) entering a parallel network?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Sum of the individual branch currents",
            "It = I1 + I2 + I3",
            "Adding the current from each independent path",
            "Total flow equals the combined flow of all branches"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is a parallel configuration used for domestic socket outlets instead of a series configuration?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Every load receives the full supply voltage",
        "Components or branches operate independently",
        "If one appliance fails or is turned off, the others continue to work",
        "Voltage is common across all branches",
        "Adding more appliances reduces total resistance rather than restricting total current"
      ],
      "hint": "Consider what happens to the voltage and the independence of the branches when you add or remove a load."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Circuit Configuration Analysis",
    "objective": "Synthesize the rules of series and parallel circuits to explain the impact of circuit layout on total resistance and current flow.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To master DC circuits, you must understand how the physical layout dictates the electrical behavior. In a series circuit, every resistor added is an extra hurdle for the current, increasing total resistance and lowering the total flow. Voltage is shared across these hurdles.",
      "In a parallel circuit, every resistor added is an extra 'lane' for the current to flow through, which actually reduces the total resistance of the circuit. Because every branch is connected directly across the supply, they all receive the full voltage, allowing each branch to draw its own current independently."
    ],
    "questionText": "You have two 10Ω resistors and a 20V DC supply. \n\n1. Calculate the total resistance (Rt) and total current (It) if they are connected in series. \n2. Calculate the total resistance (Rt) and total current (It) if they are reconnected in parallel. \n3. Explain why the total current in the parallel configuration is four times higher than in the series configuration, referencing voltage and resistance rules.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Series: Rt = 20Ω, It = 1A",
      "Parallel: Rt = 5Ω, It = 4A",
      "Explanation: In series, the resistances add together (10+10) which restricts current. In parallel, the total resistance drops (to 5Ω) because you have provided two paths. Furthermore, in parallel, each 10Ω resistor receives the full 20V (drawing 2A each), whereas in series, they only received 10V each."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about the 'paths' available. In series, there is one path with double the resistance. In parallel, there are two paths, and each path gets the full 'pressure' of the 20V supply."
  }
}

